Insight into 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements: the eï¬ects of element isotropy and mesh patterns
Phill-Seung Lee a, Hyuk-Chun Noh b, Klaus-Jurgen Bathe Â¨
b c

c,*

a Samsung Heavy Industries, 825-13 Yeoksam, Gangnam, Seoul 135-080, Korea Korea Concrete Institute Research Center, 635-4 Yeoksam, Gangnam, Seoul 135-703, Korea Department of Mechanical Engineering, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 77 Massachusetts Avenue, Cambridge, MA 02139, USA

Received 9 October 2006; accepted 30 October 2006 Available online 28 December 2006

Abstract In this paper, we study the convergence characteristics of some 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements. We review the formulations of three diï¬erent isotropic 3-node elements and one non-isotropic 3-node element. We analyze a clamped plate problem and a hyperboloid shell problem using various mesh topologies and present the convergence curves using the s-norm. Considering simple bending tests, we also study the transverse shear strain ï¬elds of the shell ï¬nite elements. The results and insight given are valuable for the proper use and the further development of triangular shell ï¬nite elements. Ã 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
Keywords: Shell structures; Finite elements; Triangular elements; MITC elements

1. Introduction For several decades, the ï¬nite element method has been used as a main tool to analyze shell structures in various engineering applications. However, there are still many important research challenges to increase the eï¬ectiveness of the analysis of shells [1â4]. Shells are three-dimensional structures with one dimension, the thickness, small compared to the other two dimensions. As the shell thickness decreases, shell structures can behave diï¬erently depending on the geometry, loading and boundary conditions of the shell, that is, the behavior of a shell structure belongs to one of three diï¬erent asymptotic categories: membrane-dominated, bendingdominated, or mixed shell problems [2â4]. A major diï¬culty in the development of shell ï¬nite elements is to overcome the locking phenomenon for bendingdominated shells. When the ï¬nite element approximations

*

Corresponding author. Tel.: +1 617 253 6645; fax: +1 617 253 2275. E-mail address: kjb@mit.edu (K.J. Bathe).

cannot suï¬ciently well approximate the pure bending displacement ï¬elds, membrane and shear locking occur. Then, as the shell thickness decreases, the convergence of the ï¬nite element solution rapidly deteriorates. An ideal ï¬nite element formulation would uniformly converge to the exact solution of the mathematical model irrespective of the shell geometry, asymptotic category and thickness. In addition, the convergence rate should be optimal. Of course, it is extremely hard to reach ideal (or uniformly optimal) shell ï¬nite elements but continuous eï¬orts are highly desirable. When modeling general engineering structures, some triangular ï¬nite elements are frequently used. Typically, to mesh complex shell structures, the mesh generation scheme establishes by far mostly quadrilateral elements but when these become too distorted because of geometric complexities, triangular elements are used instead. Also, triangular shell elements may be eï¬ective when these are used to represent a thin structure within tetrahedral three-dimensional element meshes, like in the analysis of rubber media reinforced by thin steel layers, or in the solution of ï¬uid-structure interactions [5]. Of course, in general, quadrilateral

0045-7949/$ - see front matter Ã 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved. doi:10.1016/j.compstruc.2006.10.006

P.S. Lee et al. / Computers and Structures 85 (2007) 404â418

405

elements can have a higher predictive capability, and therefore more research eï¬ort has been expended to develop quadrilateral shell ï¬nite element discretizations and more progress has also been achieved. Since quadrilateral elements have simpler coordinate systems and richer strain ï¬elds than triangular elements, quadrilateral shell ï¬nite elements that overcome the locking phenomenon are also easier to establish. Indeed, some quadrilateral shell elements are close to ââuniformly optimalââ [1,2]. The two basic approaches used to formulate general shell elements [1,2,6] are the formulations in which plate bending and membrane actions are superimposed and the formulations based on three-dimensional continuum mechanics [1,2,7]. However, discretizations based on elements in which the membrane and bending actions are superimposed may not converge in the solution of general shell problems [2], and we focus in our work on a general continuum mechanics based approach. The resulting elements are attractive because they can be used for any shell geometry and, also, a linear formulation can directly and elegantly be extended to general nonlinear formulations. However, the elements need be developed in mixed formulations, since the pure displacement formulation locks [1,2,8]. In particular, the displacement-based 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite element (QUAD3) locks severely. One approach is to use selective reduced integration resulting in the SRI3 element. Recently, using the MITC1 (Mixed Interpolation of Tensorial Components) technique for triangular shell ï¬nite elements, a 3-node MITC triangular shell ï¬nite element (MITC3) has been developed [9]. Its performance has been studied for various shell problems using well-established benchmark procedures. The element is very attractive because its formulation is simple and general, and, in particular, the behavior of the element is isotropic, that is, the stiï¬ness matrix of the triangular element does not depend on the sequence of node numbering. However, the element is not ââuniformly optimalââ, that is, some locking is present and seen in the solution of the clamped plate problem and the hyperboloid shell problem [9]. This deï¬ciency provides a motivation to further study the element behavior. It is well known that triangular shell ï¬nite elements give very diï¬erent solution accuracy depending on the mesh pattern used for a shell problem [1,10]. Hence, to evaluate a triangular shell ï¬nite element, speciï¬c diï¬erent meshes should be used to test the element performance. In addition also an appropriate norm need be used to measure the error [11]. Our objective in this paper is to further study the convergence behavior of the MITC3 shell ï¬nite element and some other 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements when using diï¬erent mesh patterns and the s-norm proposed by Hiller and Bathe [11]. Also, to obtain insight into the reasons why the diï¬erent results are obtained, we study
The MITC technique has been successfully used for developing highperformance quadrilateral shell ï¬nite elements, namely the MITC4, MITC9 and MITC16 elements.
1

the transverse shear strain ï¬elds of the 3-node shell ï¬nite elements in simple bending problems. While we use exclusively 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements in these studies, we recognize that â as pointed out above already â in practice these elements will frequently not be used alone but only when necessary together with quadrilateral elements. However, this fact does not diminish the importance of our study. In the following sections, we ï¬rst review the formulations of four 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements and their strain ï¬elds. Next, considering a fully clamped plate problem and a hyperboloid shell problem, we study the convergence of the shell ï¬nite elements depending on the mesh patterns used. To further investigate the behavior of the shell ï¬nite elements, we then study the transverse shear strain ï¬elds in two simple plate bending problems. Since the s-norm is used in the convergence studies, we give in an Appendix, a general scheme for the numerical calculation of this norm. 2. Formulations of 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements We brieï¬y review the formulations of four diï¬erent 3node triangular shell ï¬nite elements: three isotropic elements and one non-isotropic element. Here, we only show the covariant strain ï¬elds of the elements since, once these ï¬elds are known, it is straightforward to establish the stiï¬ness matrices for the analysis of shell structures [1]. 2.1. Covariant strain ï¬elds of 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements The geometry of a q-node continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite element is described by ~ s; nÃ Â¼ xÃ°r;
