shell problem. Although the SRI3 and NIT3 elements contain a spurious zero energy mode â and can therefore not be recommended for practical use â we evaluated these elements in our study merely to obtain insight into element behaviors. Regarding the convergence behavior of the 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements, we have made the following observations: â¢ In the fully clamped plate problem, the QUAD3 and SRI3 shell ï¬nite elements severely lock regardless of the mesh patterns used. In the regular meshes, the MITC3 element shows some locking but frequently acceptable for practical analysis, and when the cross mesh of the MITC3 shell ï¬nite element is used, almost optimal convergence is obtained. The NIT3 shell ï¬nite element shows optimal convergence when for a speciï¬c mesh pattern the tying points of the element are aligned as used in the MITC4 element, but locking is seen in other cases, that is, the solution accuracy given by the NIT3 element highly depends on the mesh patterns used and on the element orientation in a given mesh pattern. â¢ In the hyperboloid shell problem, severe locking is seen for the QUAD3 and SRI3 shell ï¬nite elements. The MITC3 shell ï¬nite element shows alleviated locking in the regular mesh and much better results in the cross mesh. For the NIT3 element, the results highly depend on the element orientation in a given mesh pattern. We also studied the transverse shear strain ï¬elds and strain energies stored in two simple plate bending problems. This simple study gave some insight why there is the mesh-dependent behavior of the MITC3 shell ï¬nite element in the fully clamped plate problem and the hyperboloid shell problem.

Clearly, the only nodal displacements and rotations that satisfy the pure bending condition are a2 Â¼ b2 Â¼ w2 Â¼ 0; Ã°44Ã

and this implies locking in this case. Similarly, it is simple to show that the QUAD3 and SRI3 elements lock in this plate problem for all three meshes used. These results are in correspondence with the ï¬nding that, while of course the QUAD3, SRI3, and MITC3 elements pass the membrane patch tests, of these elements only the MITC3 element passes also the bending patch test [1]. 5. Conclusions Our objective was to obtain insight into the convergence behavior of 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements in bending-dominated problems depending on the mesh patterns used. We reviewed the formulations of four 3-node triangular shell ï¬nite elements and their strain ï¬elds, the QUAD3, SRI3, MITC3 and NIT3 elements, and presented the solutions of a fully clamped plate problem and a hyperboloid

P.S. Lee et al. / Computers and Structures 85 (2007) 404â418

417

Based on the results of this study, it is obvious that for the benchmark tests of triangular shell ï¬nite elements, various mesh patterns need to be considered, and, in addition, when non-isotropic shell ï¬nite elements are tested, their performance should also be studied considering their various orientations in the given mesh patterns.

Appendix. A general scheme for the numerical calculation of the s-norm We here propose a numerical procedure to calculate the s-norm for shell ï¬nite element solutions with general types of elements and general meshes. The reference numerical solution given by ~ref is u employed instead of the exact solution and the target numerical solution given by ~h is compared with this referu ence solution. The major diï¬culty of the s-norm calculation is to establish the mapping points between the reference mesh and the target mesh. We evaluate the integration in Eq. (21) using the Gauss integration technique in the reference domain. Figs. 16(a) and (b) shows the reference mesh and the target mesh. In the ï¬gures, (rref, sref, nref) are the isoparametric coordinates of the Gauss integration point of the element in the refer-

ence mesh, and (rh, sh, nh) are the corresponding isoparametric coordinates of the corresponding element in the target mesh. Our goal is to ï¬nd the corresponding element and to establish (rh, sh) for the given (rref, sref) because nh = nref in shells. The ï¬rst step is to ï¬nd the corresponding element in the target mesh. From the given (rref, sref) of the element in the reference mesh, we calculate the global coordinates (xref, yref, zref) xref Â¼ zref Â¼
